The measurement of the plates are both

I had ar500 plates but 46100 material is by far a lot better. Some people say AR500 are military steel but the military never uses ar500. title: For Sale:   Winchester Model 70 Short Rifle Pre-War Carbine
postcontent: Pre-64 Winchester model 70. Serial Number 21361 was produced BEFORE WW2 and was produced as a factory 20 inch barrel SHORT RIFLE in 1939. Caliber is 30 Govt'06 and there are NO Non-Factory holes or alterations. The rear bridge has NEVER been drilled and tapped. Original sights are present and the front sight is an integral part of the barrel so it is impossible to fake. Early features including the clover leaf tang and early style safety. Excellent bore and mechanics. Nearly all of the original blue remains and this short rifle has seen limited and careful use. Solid stock with strong original checkering and original butt plate. Perhaps a light coat of oil has been applied to the stock long ago. It looks great with excellent wood to metal fit. These factory short rifle model 70's are perhaps one of the most difficult variations to find especially with NO extra holes in the rear bridge as most were scoped up over the years. This is a great model 70 in collector condition sure to appreciate in value.

location: east side of okc, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent:
This is a low round cound kahr pm40, under 100rds. Its comes with a second, new, cm40 top end I acquired and then was ported by a gunsmith. The Kahr factory couldnt do it any slicker.
Either top end works 100%. Firing the ported top end, I really cant notice any increase in muzzle (or port) flash or fireball.
The ported barrel, when fired, is subtly flatter, less flip. It also does take the "sting" away from firing this pocket cannon, compared to the regular barrel, so it is noticeably softer.

This would be a good setup to practice with the ported top end, put the wear on that, and then carry the normal top end.

Comes with 2 mags, a 6 and 7rounder, and box, papers, lock, etc.

looking for $625 obo

title: For Sale:  CZ vz 27 Ceska Zbrojovka A.S. V Praza 7.65 .32 acp
postcontent:
The vz. 27 is a Czech semi-automatic pistol, based on the pistole vz. 24, and chambered for 7.65 mm Browning/.32 ACP. It is often designated the CZ 27 after the naming scheme used by the Česká zbrojovka factory for post-World War II commercial products. However, it is correctly known as vz. 27, an abbreviation of the Czech "vzor 27", or "Model 27".

After the German occupation of Czechoslovakia in 1938 the pistol was folded into the German armed and police forces as the P27. Construction of the pistol continued in Czechoslovakia until the 1950s. Allegedly, the Czech military sold five and a half thousand surplus vz. 27s to the Swiss in 1973 for half a million marks. Between 620,000 and 650,000 were manufactured in total, 452,500 of those under German occupation. In December of 1948, a gift of five "ČZ 247" automatic variants of the pistol (based on both the vz. 24 and vz. 27) was sent to Ethiopian ruler Haile Selassie. In 1949, the vz. pistol was exported to 28 countries, including Turkey (3,286 pistols), England, South Africa, Egypt, Kenya, and Pakistan.

Known military contracts include India, Brazil, Ecuador, Bolivia, Venezuela, and Poland.

Not really interested in trades but if thats what you can do I do like new toys so I would consider the offer if its something I like. No junk though such as Jennings, Lorcin,Cobra, or High point. This is a decent quality fire arm so offer should be of similar quality

The small, pocket-sized Vz.50 was developed during late 1940s for police use and it was chambered for the marginally powerful 7.65x17 Browning ammunition. Apparently influenced by the Walther PP in design, the Vz.50 had several differences in safety and disassembly. In the early 1970s the basic design went through minor face-lift, and the "new" design received the designation of Vz.70. Many Vz.50 pistols were refurbished to Vz.70 standard, with different finish, grip panels and a slightly different safety lever. New Vz.70 pistols were also manufactured between 1970 and 1983. After the replacement in service of the older Vz.50 and Vz.70 by more modern 9mm Vz.82 pistol, most were sold as surplus, as Cz-50 and Cz-70, respectively.

The Vz.50 (commercially sold as Cz-50) is a compact pistol of all-steel construction, firing the relatively weak 7.65mm ammunition. It has a simple blowback action with a fixed barrel. The trigger is double-action, with an exposed hammer and a frame-mounted decocking safety lever. The sights are fixed. Magazines are single stack. The magazine release button is located relatively high on the left side of the frame, behind the trigger. Vz.70 (Cz-70) pistols are similar, with minor differences in the finish, shape of the safety lever and grips. Manual safety is a lever at left side of the frame, behind the trigger guard. To set on safe: pull the lever down; if the hammer was cocked, it will be automatically brought down to rest. To disengage safety: push the lever up; a red dot will appear on the frame. (info from world.guns.ru, not my words)...............
